<hl>
<seg id=1> Chuan Leepkai: Thailand will begin the election ahead of time. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Bangkok Thailand Prime Minister Chuan Leepkai said the night before last that he would begin the election ahead of time before the seven-party united government finished its term in October 2000. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> However, he added that the united government was stable at present and had the ability to carry out the economic reform plan. </seg>
<seg id=4> He said that economic reform was decisive to economic recovery and development. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> In his speech at the Overseas Journalists' Club in Thailand, Chuan Leepkai said: "We must remember that the confidence of foreign investors is closely bound up with the stability of the government and the continuity of policies." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> "We don't plan to wait until the end of the term. </seg>
<seg id=7> We make use of the time left to carry out the reform of the national economy, and lay a solid foundation for development. " </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Chuan Leepkai expressed that it had not been decided yet when we were going to dismiss the congress and begin the election ahead of time. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Thailand hasn't got rid of the crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> In addition, in his speech, Chuan Leepkai warned that Thailand hadn't got rid of the crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> He pointed that the situation at present was still "weak", and that global factors might lead Thailand off the economic target in the latter half of the year. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> However, he promised to carry out extensive reform measures and put an end to the corruption that was weakening the national economy. </seg>
</p>
